Would you like a sample GitHub Action YAML that automatically parses your commit messages and runs this Maven command?

Yes

To automate this, we will use a GitHub Action that parses your commit message using a regex pattern, determines the semantic version bump, and then triggers the Maven plugin.

GitHub Action: Auto-SemVer Schema Registration
This workflow triggers on every push. It calculates whether to bump the Major, Minor, or Patch version and then executes the apicurio-registry-maven-plugin.

YAML
name: Schema Registry Sync

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
    paths:
      - 'src/main/resources/schemas/**' # Only run if schemas change

jobs:
  register-schema:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0 # Needed to see previous tags

      - name: Determine SemVer Bump
        id: semver
        run: |
          COMMIT_MSG=$(git log -1 --pretty=%B)
          # Default to patch
          BUMP="patch"
          
          if [[ "$COMMIT_MSG" == feat* ]]; then
            BUMP="major"
          elif [[ "$COMMIT_MSG" == fix* ]] || [[ "$COMMIT_MSG" == patch* ]]; then
            BUMP="patch"
          elif [[ "$COMMIT_MSG" == chore* ]] || [[ "$COMMIT_MSG" == minor* ]]; then
            BUMP="minor"
          fi
          
          echo "bump_type=$BUMP" >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT

      - name: Calculate New Version
        id: versioning
        uses: phipsiamp/semver-action@v1
        with:
          bump: ${{ steps.semver.outputs.bump_type }}
          # This pulls the latest tag from git to calculate the next one
          github-token: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}

      - name: Set up JDK 17
        uses: actions/setup-java@v3
        with:
          java-version: '17'
          distribution: 'temurin'
          cache: 'maven'

      - name: Register Schema with Apicurio
        run: |
          mvn apicurio-registry:register \
            -Dcustom.schema.version=${{ steps.versioning.outputs.version }} \
            -Dregistry.url=${{ secrets.APICURIO_URL }}
How this works in your Quarkus environment:
Commit Trigger: You commit a change to your .avsc file with the message feat: add user profile fields.

Logic Logic: The script sees feat and selects a Major bump.

Version Calculation: If your current version in Git is 1.2.1, the action calculates the next version as 2.0.0.

Maven Injection: It runs Maven, passing -Dcustom.schema.version=2.0.0.

Apicurio Update: The plugin sends the schema to Apicurio. Because you are passing a string 2.0.0 to the version field, Apicurio saves it exactly as that string instead of the default integer 1.

Pro-Tip for Quarkus Integration
Since you are now using SemVer (e.g., 1.0.0, 2.0.0), ensure your Quarkus application's Kafka Consumer is configured to handle these versions correctly.

If you want your consumer to always grab the latest Major version 1 even if version 2 exists (to avoid breaking changes), you can refine your ArtifactResolverStrategy to filter by version patterns:

Properties
# Force consumer to stay within a specific major version range
mp.messaging.incoming.orders.apicurio.registry.version=1.*
Would you like to see how to implement a "Schema Compatibility Check" in this pipeline so the build fails if a developer introduces a breaking change?

Yes

Integrating a Compatibility Check into your pipeline is the ultimate "safety net." It prevents a developer from pushing a "fix" that accidentally deletes a required field, which would normally crash all your running Quarkus consumers.

Apicurio has a built-in goal for this: apicurio-registry:test-update.

1. Update the GitHub Action
We will add a "Validation" step before the registration step. If the new schema is incompatible with the existing one (e.g., removing a field without a default value), the build will fail, and the schema won't be registered.

YAML
      - name: Test Schema Compatibility
        run: |
          mvn apicurio-registry:test-update \
            -Dcustom.schema.version=${{ steps.versioning.outputs.version }} \
            -Dregistry.url=${{ secrets.APICURIO_URL }}
        # If this step fails, the next "Register" step will never run.

      - name: Register Schema with Apicurio
        run: |
          mvn apicurio-registry:register \
            -Dcustom.schema.version=${{ steps.versioning.outputs.version }} \
            -Dregistry.url=${{ secrets.APICURIO_URL }}
2. Configure Compatibility Levels
In your pom.xml, you need to define how strict Apicurio should be. For Avro, BACKWARD is the most common choice (ensures new code can read old data).

Update your plugin configuration in pom.xml:

XML
<artifact>
    <groupId>messaging-group</groupId>
    <artifactId>orders-value</artifactId>
    <version>${custom.schema.version}</version>
    <type>AVRO</type>
    <file>${project.basedir}/src/main/resources/schemas/order.avsc</file>
    <ifExists>RETURN_OR_UPDATE</ifExists>
    <configProperties>
        <property>
            <name>compatibilityMode</name>
            <value>BACKWARD</value>
        </property>
    </configProperties>
</artifact>
3. How it works in practice
Imagine your current schema has a field orderId.

The "Fix" (Safe): A developer adds a new optional field discountCode with a default value of null. The test-update goal passes. The version bumps to 1.0.1.

The "Break" (Unsafe): A developer renames orderId to id. The test-update goal detects that existing consumers expecting orderId will fail. The Maven command returns a non-zero exit code, the GitHub Action stops, and your Registry remains safe.

4. Summary of the Innovative Workflow
By combining these steps, you have created a professional-grade Schema Registry lifecycle:

Git-Driven Versioning: Your 1.0.0 vs 1 issue is solved by injecting SemVer strings via CI.

Semantic Meaning: Commit prefixes (feat, fix) automatically dictate the version impact.

Automated Safety: No "poison" schemas can reach the registry thanks to the compatibility test.

Quarkus Integration: Your app uses the custom DeserializationFailureHandler to handle any edge cases that slip through.

One Last Tip: The "Global" Rule
If you want every schema in your company to follow these rules without configuring them one-by-one in the pom.xml, you can set a Global Rule in the Apicurio Registry UI or via their API:

Rule Type: Compatibility

Configuration: BACKWARD

Would you like me to show you the curl command to set this compatibility rule globally so it applies to all future schemas automatically?

Yes

Setting a global rule is the most efficient way to ensure governance across your entire organization. It means even if a developer forgets to include the compatibility property in their pom.xml, the Registry itself will reject any breaking changes at the server level.

1. Set Global Compatibility via Curl
Apicurio provides a REST API for administrative tasks. You can run this command to force BACKWARD compatibility for every artifact in the registry.

Bash
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8080/apis/registry/v2/admin/rules" \
     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
     -d '{
           "type": "COMPATIBILITY",
           "config": "BACKWARD"
         }'
BACKWARD: Consumers using the new schema can read data produced with the previous schema.

BACKWARD_TRANSITIVE: Consumers using the new schema can read data produced by all previous versions (highly recommended for long-running topics).

2. Verify the Rule
To ensure the rule is active and check its current configuration, use this GET request:

Bash
curl -X GET "http://localhost:8080/apis/registry/v2/admin/rules/COMPATIBILITY"
