To consume from both orders-v1 and orders-v2 simultaneously in a single method, we use the Kafka Multi-Topic Subscription feature in SmallRye Reactive Messaging.

Since these artifacts have different schemas (major versions), the innovation here is to use a Generic Avro Record or a Common Interface so your Java code doesn't crash when it encounters different data structures.

1. Configure Quarkus for Multi-Topic Consumption
Instead of a single topic, use a Regular Expression or a Comma-Separated List for the topic configuration.

application.properties

Properties
# Listen to all versions of the orders topic
mp.messaging.incoming.orders-in.topic=orders-v1,orders-v2

# Use GenericData$Record to handle different schema structures in one method
mp.messaging.incoming.orders-in.value.deserializer=io.apicurio.registry.serde.avro.AvroKafkaDeserializer
# Ensure we don't try to map to a specific class immediately
mp.messaging.incoming.orders-in.apicurio.registry.avro-datum-provider=io.apicurio.registry.serde.avro.GenericAvroDatumProvider
2. Implement the "Universal Consumer" Logic
Using GenericRecord allows you to inspect the fields dynamically. This is the "Bridge" pattern—handling old and new data formats in one place.

Java
import org.apache.avro.generic.GenericRecord;
import org.eclipse.microprofile.reactive.messaging.Incoming;
import jakarta.enterprise.context.ApplicationScoped;

@ApplicationScoped
public class OrderMigrationConsumer {

    @Incoming("orders-in")
    public void processAllVersions(GenericRecord record) {
        // Innovation: Handle both versions based on field existence
        String orderId;
        
        if (record.getSchema().getField("orderId") != null) {
            // Logic for V1
            orderId = record.get("orderId").toString();
            System.out.println("Processing V1 Order: " + orderId);
        } else {
            // Logic for V2 (where maybe it was renamed to 'id')
            orderId = record.get("id").toString();
            System.out.println("Processing V2 Order: " + orderId);
        }

        // Common processing logic here...
    }
}
3. Why this is an Innovative Migration Strategy
Zero Downtime: You don't have to stop the world to upgrade. You deploy this "Bridge" consumer, then start producing v2 messages.

Smooth Cutover: Once the v1 topic is empty, you can simply remove the orders-v1 from the configuration and delete the old schema.

Schema Discovery: By using GenericAvroDatumProvider, the app automatically asks Apicurio: "What is the schema for this specific message?" for every record, allowing it to swap logic on the fly.

